<br>
Mages have the great ability to summon up a warrior of sorts in the guise of an elemental. With the aid of their elemental and the power of their damage spells mages are a definite benefit to any group, but they can often be found adventuring with just their pet at their sides.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Does that say &quot;feeder of mana&quot;? (sorry I couldn't pull the instruction manual's description down since station.sony.com is undergoing maintanace)<br>
<br>
Ya wanna talk teamwork aye?<br>
<br>
Necros: raid usefulness went to &lt;crap&gt; with the advent of t-rods........hence the advent of DoT stacking......ohh thats teamwork, kick the necros raid usefulness for our benefit.......Yet the necro's in general were GLAD they lost the &quot;mana whore&quot; label, guess thats teamwork too. (a weeee bit sarcastic)<br>
<br>
Clerics:  demand for these suffered with the advent of t-rods.......hence the advent of VI trying to appease them and ALLOW them to solo semi efficiently, kick the demand for clerics so we can benefit......Yet the clerics in general saw this as a good thing since they get some cool sheeeet out of it I guess this is teamwork.(a weeee bit sarcastic)<br>
<br>
Druids/shamans: Demand for these as back-up healers droped since the advent of t-rods.......hence yet again the advent of DoT stacking (though stated it was for necro's it helps these guys too), and this FAMOUS 75% CH's that were on test (sorry, did they make it into the game?  Haven't cared to ask any of them or even look for it for my druid) to bring their demand  back up a bit (not really a shaman thing more of a druid thing, since shaman will be slowing and debuffing not really healing per se), yes kick the druids/shamen down a bit so we can benefit......Ok the droods beeeeech about everything, even if they had a 100% CH it wouldn't be enough to shut them up anyway I guess this is teamwork.(a weeee bit sarcastic)<br>
<br>
Groups can do what it used to take guilds to do by simply adding 1 soletary mage.  Thats teamwork?  6 people can now do what it used to take 18+ people to pull off, I assume you consider this teamwork.  What about the other 12?  Sure you &quot;a magician&quot; now have a role, and yet you ignore that you NEVER had this role prior to the advent of t-rods and you in a sence &quot;nerfed&quot; other classes usefulness in ALOT of circumstances. <br>
<br>
Either way your not saying those who &quot;love&quot; t-rods have better social skills and know what teamwork is.  Naw those are the same ones that left half their &quot;team&quot; at the airport.  <br>
<br>
Since DoT stacking, cleric upgrades, miniCH's, the other half of the team has a USE again now.  So I am not as strongly against t-rods as I used to be, it just sucks to hear in /guild &quot;well if xxmagexx is coming then 20 of you will have to leave since we wont need you and all you'll be adding is lag&quot;.  I am a team player, as such if my going means others will be pushed aside, because of 1 spell, I will ALWAYS chose not to attend in behalf of the part of the team that would have been ditched to the side (druids included).<br>
<br>
This has happened, many of you here have boasted about it(albiet other threads), yet you want to talk about teamwork?<br>
<br>
I agree theres ALOT of fights that there is no need to t-rod, it's the clerics and raid leaders that have to be convinced of that.  Yes, a lvl 60 guildie cleric hasn't played in 4 months after I ripped her for &quot;needing&quot; rods in every single fight (even if it was a lvl 1 rat she was &quot;rod damn it rod&quot;), my life has never been better, and I havn't had to summon rods mid battle again.<br>
<br>
BTW when you type &quot;mod rod&quot; I can only assume that you are talking about a mod rod, if you are meaning t-rod (or trod) then could you take the .0000002 seconds diferenciate and/or clarify which one you are referencing?  It is superficial to talk about mod rods at all, they have NO practical use, if a guild is asking for mod rods then they need some serious help, they should be asking for a mage that can do better than those cheese mod rods.  I am the type of guy who &quot;if&quot; someone told me they needed mod rods, I would summon them mod rods and eat t-rods to gain my mana back.  As such if they ask for &quot;ouch sticks&quot;, &quot;rods&quot; (I ask for clarification here), &quot;them clicky things&quot;, &quot;mana bars&quot;, &quot;mind sticks&quot;, etc etc etc I simply do not answer as I have no clue what those items are and/or how they expect me to help them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unaladini.showPublicProfile?language=EN>naladini</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 431<br> <font color=#333333>(9/20/02 7:26:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=328.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: teamwork?</span><hr size=1> Those are fair points to make. Not every class is balanced, and time changes the game world (more AA's, FT items, etc). The rich get richer could be an analogy used here.....<br>
<br>
Regarding the role of the mage: I believe we CAN do anything. We're only limited by the effects of the items we summon. eg. I'd love to see VI give mages a spell that conjures a No Rent TL to Bind clicky item that we could give/sell to melee types. Will they? Probably not, but it would be within the definition of our class.<br>
<br>
To me teamwork means a group (team) of people working together to meet an objective. There are many subjective ways to interpret this. I'd classify the example of staying home so 10 more people can go on a raid as 'taking one for the team'. Honestly, if 10 people weren't able to go on Raid A b/c you decided to go, then they'd have a nice start on a group for Raid B......<br>
<br>
The guy holding the football for the placekicker is still a part of the footbal team, right? Actually, he's usually a quarterback, just not as good as the starter. So he's asked to play a different role, but is still a part of the team.<br>
<br>
PS. One other point to make. One class gaining a skill should not be considered a NERF of another class. This entire game and its system of balance was created around increasing abilities, effects, items, etc. If one class becomes less useful because of another class' ability, VI needs to give new roles/responsibilities to the class that lost out..... <p>Naladini <BR>
Elementalist of the 52nd Season-Stormhammer<BR>
